  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over the past several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged primarily as a response to organized crime activities\n- Initially focused on criminal proceeds from drug trafficking\n- United States passed key early legislation like the Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n\n2. Major Milestones:\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act in the US\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 1990s: International expansion of anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act significantly expanded reporting requirements\n\n3. Key Legislative Developments:\n- Criminalized intentional money laundering\n- Required financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Established comprehensive reporting and record-keeping standards\n- Created international cooperation mechanisms\n\n4. Global Expansion:\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- Increasing international standardization of AML regulations\n- Broader focus beyond drug trafficking to terrorism financing, corruption\n\n5. Modern Trends:\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency-related regulations\n- Increased international information sharing\n- More sophisticated technological detection methods\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with technological and criminal innovations.",
